body:
### [EDIT] Summary:
* Non-blocking (`<=`) assignments in `initial` blocks are converted to blocking (`=`).
* As a result, non-blocking assignments after a `@(posedge clk) ;` delay in an `initial` block don't behave as expected.
* This also affects non-blocking assignments in **tasks** called from the `initial` block.
* This doesn't happen in `always` blocks, so currently a workaround is to convert the `initial` block to an `always` block ending in `$finish;` or `forever;`.

*(This is a summary of the issue including the conclusions that arose during its discussion; below is the original issue report.)*

________

### Problem description:
I usually create my testbenches so that the signal generation section uses some idiom for "wait for the next clock rising edge" rather than waiting a fixed amount of time.  This makes the signals appear as if they were generated from a synchronous circuit.
In the case of [System]Verilog, I achieve this by adding a `@(posedge clk) ;` statement inside the `initial begin` block, and then assigning to a signal using `<=`.  The expected result is identical to doing that assignment inside the `@(posedge clk)`, but gives me more freedom to write readable testbenches.  This syntax may seem a bit strange, but it has worked in every other simulator I've tested, and I understand it is a valid use of Verilog.

However, it appears that Verilator treats this `<=` assignment as a blocking `=` assignment, assigning the value immediately, rather than "after the clock edge", and the result is not as expected.

### Example code:
```verilog
`timescale 1ns/100ps

module T_verilator_posedge;

reg clk = 1;
reg [7:0] d = 0;
reg [7:0] q = 0;

// Clock generation
always #0.5 clk = ~clk;

// Input signal generation
initial begin
    // Initialize VCD dump
    $dumpfile("T_verilator_posedge.vcd");
    $dumpvars(0, T_verilator_posedge);

    d <= 0;
    repeat (5) @(posedge clk);
    d <= 1;
    @(posedge clk);
    d <= 2;
    @(posedge clk);
    d <= 3;
    @(posedge clk);
    d <= 4;
    @(posedge clk);
    d <= 0;
    repeat (5) @(posedge clk);
    $finish;
end

// Unit under test (flip-flop)
always @(posedge clk)
    q <= d;

endmodule
```

Compiled with:
```sh
verilator -CFLAGS -fcoroutines --binary --trace -Wno-fatal T_verilator_posedge.v
```

### Expected result:
The `q` signal is delayed one clock cycle after `d`.  This is the case if I simulate the file with Icarus Verilog.
![expected_iverilog](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/assets/6584870/88fd9afe-b6ab-4419-b42b-e1b24798ba62)

### Obtained result:
The `q` signal is simultaneous to the `d` signal.  This is the case if I simulate the file with Verilator 5.026.
![obtained_verilator](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/assets/6584870/640b293a-16e5-4e7d-8b12-ab2ae439979f)

### Verilator version:
Verilator 5.026, freshly compiled.
```
# verilator --version
Verilator 5.026 2024-06-15 rev v5.026
```

### Temporary workaround:
~~For the time being, I'm adding a `#0.1;` after each `@(posedge clk);`.  It works, but it's not a perfect solution.~~
EDIT: An easier and better workaround is to convert the `initial` block to `always`, which seems not to be affected by this.
